  "prompt": "What is the difference between quality control and quality assurance?",
  "response": "Quality Control (QC) and Quality Assurance (QA) are both important aspects of quality management, but they have distinct differences:\n\nQuality Control (QC):\n1. Focuses on identifying and fixing defects in finished products\n2. Reactive approach - checks products after they are produced\n3. Involves inspection, testing, and measuring product characteristics\n4. Aims to ensure products meet specific standards\n5. Typically occurs at the end of the production process\n6. Identifies and corrects specific product issues\n\nQuality Assurance (QA):\n1. Focuses on preventing defects before they occur\n2. Proactive approach - establishes processes to prevent quality problems\n3. Involves creating and implementing quality management systems\n4. Aims to improve overall process and prevent quality issues\n5. Occurs throughout the entire production process\n6. Develops and maintains standards and procedures\n\nKey differences:\n- QC is about finding and fixing problems\n- QA is about preventing problems from happening\n- QC is product-oriented\n- QA is process-oriented\n- QC is a subset of QA\n- QA provides the framework within which QC operates\n\nBoth are essential for maintaining high-quality products and customer satisfaction.",
